aa(lp6
VI have passionate opinions about gender equality,
p7
aVbut I worry that to freely accept the label of "feminist,"
p8
aVwould not be fair to good feminists.
p9
aa(lp10
VI'm a feminist, but I'm a rather bad one.
p11
aVOh, so I call myself a Bad Feminist.
p12
aVOr at least, I wrote an essay,
p13
aVand then I wrote a book called "Bad Feminist,"
p14
aVand then in interviews, people started calling me The Bad Feminist.
p15
aV(Laughter)
p16
aa(lp17
VSo, what started as a bit of an inside joke with myself
p18
aVand a willful provocation,
p19
aVhas become a thing.
p20
aa(lp21
VLet me take a step back.
p22
aVWhen I was younger,
p23
aVmostly in my teens and 20s,
p24
aVI had strange ideas about feminists
p25
aVas hairy, angry, man-hating, sex-hating women \u2014
p26
aVas if those are bad things.
p27
aV(Laughter)
p28
aVThese days, I look at how women are treated the world over,
p29
aVand anger, in particular, seems like a perfectly reasonable response.
p30
aa(lp31
VBut back then,
p32
aVI worried about the tone people used
p33
aVwhen suggesting I might be a feminist.
p34
aVThe feminist label was an accusation,
p35
aVit was an "F" word, and not a nice one.
p36
aVI was labeled a woman who doesn't play by the rules,
p37
aVwho expects too much,
p38
aVwho thinks far too highly of myself,
p39
aVby daring to believe I'm equal \u2014 (Coughs) \u2014 superior to a man.
p40
aVYou don't want to be that rebel woman,
p41
aVuntil you realize that you very much are that woman,
p42
aVand cannot imagine being anyone else.
p43
aa(lp44
VAs I got older, I began to accept
p45
aVthat I am, indeed, a feminist, and a proud one.
p46
aVI hold certain truths to be self-evident:
p47
aVWomen are equal to men.
p48
aVWe deserve equal pay for equal work.
p49
aVWe have the right to move through the world as we choose,
p50
aVfree from harassment or violence.
p51
aVWe have the right to easy, affordable access to birth control,
p52
aVand reproductive services.
p53
aVWe have the right to make choices about our bodies,
p54
aVfree from legislative oversight or evangelical doctrine.
p55
aVWe have the right to respect.
p56
aa(lp57
VThere's more.
p58
aVWhen we talk about the needs of women,
p59
aVwe have to consider the other identities we inhabit.
p60
aVWe are not just women.
p61
aVWe are people with different bodies,
p62
aVgender expressions, faiths, sexualities,
p63
aVclass backgrounds, abilities, and so much more.
p64
aVWe need to take into account
p65
aVthese differences and how they affect us,
p66
aVas much as we account for what we have in common.
p67
aVWithout this kind of inclusion, our feminism is nothing.
p68
aa(lp69
VI hold these truths to be self-evident, but let me be clear:
p70
aVI'm a mess.
p71
aVI am full of contradictions.
p72
aVThere are many ways in which I'm doing feminism wrong.
p73
